{
  "Jahmyr Gibbs": { "summary": "Jahmyr Gibbs is coming off his best season yet, totaling 1,839 scrimmage yards and 18 touchdowns across 17 games in 2025 — good for RB3 in half-PPR. With David Montgomery traded to Houston, he enters 2026 as Detroit's unquestioned lead back, poised to absorb the additional touches as a true three-down workhorse. He's a three-time Pro Bowler before his age-25 season and one of the most complete backs in the game. Gibbs should be taken either #1 or #2 overall in half-PPR formats.", "published": true },
  "Bijan Robinson": { "summary": "Bijan Robinson earned first-team All-Pro honors in 2025 after leading the NFL with 2,298 scrimmage yards, the most in Falcons history, on 287 carries and 79 receptions. He enters 2026 with an even cleaner path to the end zone after Tyler Allgeier, who scored eight rushing TDs last season, departed in free agency. Despite quarterback uncertainty in Atlanta, Robinson has produced at an elite level in every season of his career. With a cleaner path to the end zone than ever before and elite production in every season of his career, Robinson is one of the most compelling early-round investments in 2026.", "published": true },
  "Ja'Marr Chase": { "summary": "Ja'Marr Chase put up 125 catches for 1,412 yards in 2025 on a team that finished 6-11, showcasing his ability to produce regardless of what's happening around him. He enters 2026 as the near consensus WR1 in fantasy drafts, with Joe Burrow healthy and Tee Higgins returning as a legitimate complementary threat. At just 26 years old, his peak may still be ahead of him. With Burrow healthy and a full supporting cast around him, Chase is the rare receiver with both a sky-high floor and legitimate WR1 upside from start to finish.", "published": true },
  "Puka Nacua": { "summary": "Puka Nacua led the NFL in receptions in 2025 with 129 catches for 1,715 yards and 10 touchdowns, earning the top PFF receiving grade among all wide receivers. He returns in 2026 as the clear WR1 in Los Angeles with Matthew Stafford healthy and an offense built around getting him the ball. Entering just his third NFL season and having yet to show a true ceiling, Nacua is one of the most exciting early-round receivers in 2026 fantasy drafts.", "published": true },
  "Jaxon Smith-Njigba": { "summary": "Jaxon Smith-Njigba won the 2025 NFL Offensive Player of the Year award after leading the league with 1,793 receiving yards on 119 catches and 10 touchdowns, becoming the highest-paid wide receiver in league history on a new extension. He commanded a 32.6% target share (the highest in the NFL) in Seattle's run-heavy offense and carried the Seahawks to a Super Bowl. As the reigning Offensive Player of the Year and the highest-paid receiver in NFL history, JSN enters 2026 as one of the most locked-in WR1 options on the board.", "published": true },
  "Christian McCaffrey": { "summary": "Christian McCaffrey posted 2,126 scrimmage yards and 17 touchdowns in 2025, finishing as the RB1 despite averaging just 3.9 yards per carry, a testament to his elite receiving production of 102 catches for 924 yards. Entering his age-30 season, durability remains the question after he led the NFL in touches and missed 13 games in 2024. When healthy, McCaffrey is the most complete back in football — but his injury history makes him a boom-or-bust early-round pick that requires a handcuff strategy.", "published": true },
  "Jonathan Taylor": { "summary": "Jonathan Taylor led the NFL in both rushing attempts (323) and rushing touchdowns (18) in 2025, totaling 1,585 rushing yards with 46 receptions for 378 yards. He enters 2026 as the unquestioned bell cow in Indianapolis, with a healthy Daniel Jones expected back under center. As the NFL's leading rusher and touchdown scorer in 2025, Taylor enters 2026 as one of the most reliable workhorse backs available in the early rounds.", "published": true },
  "De'Von Achane": { "summary": "De'Von Achane recorded a career-high 1,838 scrimmage yards and 12 touchdowns in 2025 while leading the NFL with a 5.7 yards per carry average (all while serving as the centerpiece of a Dolphins offense that lost Tyreek Hill in Week 4). He signed a four-year, $68M extension this offseason and is locked in as Miami's featured back heading into a rebuild year with Malik Willis at quarterback. Achane's elite efficiency makes him a compelling early-round target even in a rebuilding offensive environment.", "published": true },
  "Amon-Ra St. Brown": { "summary": "Amon-Ra St. Brown has posted 100+ receptions, 1,000+ yards, and double-digit touchdowns in each of the past four seasons, a run matched only by Marvin Harrison, Antonio Brown, Davante Adams, and Stefon Diggs. His 2025 line of 117 catches for 1,401 yards and 11 TDs earned him his fourth straight Pro Bowl. St. Brown is one of the most reliable WR1 options available at his price in 2026 drafts and a guy with an extremely safe floor, having finished WR3 for 3 straight seasons.", "published": true },
  "CeeDee Lamb": { "summary": "CeeDee Lamb posted 1,077 yards and three touchdowns across 14 games in 2025 — a down year by his standards, partly due to injury and partly due to George Pickens' emergence as a co-star. It was still his fifth straight 1,000-yard season, and he out-targeted Pickens by 2.6 per game in games both played. With Prescott healthy and Dallas returning one of the NFL's top passing offenses, Lamb is a strong bounce-back candidate with WR1 upside in 2026.", "published": true },
